Currently the setup involves 1 TI LaunchXL 28069M, with an attached BoostXL 8305 as a Motor Driver.

Also attached is a breakout board made by Politecnico Milano, which includes 3 rotary potentiometers and extension pins.

The Coil is attached to Channels A and B.
The hall sensor with its makeshift breakout board gets 5V and Ground from J5 (I believe), and returns data over ADC Pin A4
The 3 Potentiometers are attached on B3, A3 and A5; of which I only use the leftmost, Pot3 (B3)

For an exact breakdown of the code, just read the code, specifically MAGLEV_adc.c is most relevant, although MAGLEV_pid.c is also important.
Note that DutyLimit is set occasionally in MAGLEV_interrupts.c.

The broad structure is best found on the poster, which is slightly inaccurate. 
Broadly, the program reads a hall sensor, feeds the data to a Position PID controller, which feeds to a current PID controller, 
    which directs a PWM signal to the Coil's supply. 

Note that the hall sensor reading gets corrected by a function dependent on current, which is not detailed there.
The output of the Position PID is scaled by a linearisation factor that I based off of measurements of Force respective to height and current.
The DutyLimit is mostly useful for development; if ever too much current is drawn or an undervoltage is detected, 
    the PWM's Duty is limited to the point where that no longer occurs

